> Tip: Welcome to your new space

> To start, you might want to:

>
> Customise this overview using the edit icon at the top right of this page.
>
>
> Create a new page by clicking the + in the space sidebar, then go ahead and fill it with plans, ideas, or anything else your heart desires.

3. Algorithm:a. Calculate Expected_Store_Orderi. Expected_Store_Order_Raw = MAX(Target_Store – NetTotalStock_Store, 0)ii. Round the value wrt to PackageSize_Store & Package Size Roundingthreshold to calculate Expected_Store_Orderb. Calculate Forecast_Part_Of_Demandi. If Expected_Store_Order > 0 Then: Forecast_DCCP – (Expected_Store_Order- Expected_Store_Order_Raw)ii. If Expected_Store_Order <= 0 Then: Target_Store + Forecast_DCCP -NetTotalStock_Storeiii. Forecast_Part_Of_Demand_Raw = MAX(Forecast_Part_Of_Demand_Raw, 0)iv. Round Forecast_Part_Of_Demand wrt PackageSize_Store & Package SizeRounding thresholdv. Calculate the final “Forecast_Part_Of_Demand” by using a roundingparameter, Example:1. Forecast_Part_Of_Demand = Forecast_Part_Of_Demand_Raw + 0.5* (Forecast_Part_Of_Demand_Rounded -Forecast_Part_Of_Demand_Raw)c. Aggregate product-store-warehouse data to product-warehouse leveli. Agg. Expected Expected_Store_Order & Forecast_Part_Of_Demandd

ouse data to product-warehouse leveli. Agg. Expected Expected_Store_Order & Forecast_Part_Of_Demandd. Estimate product-warehouse St Dev by using Forecast_Part_Of_Demand & abcvaluese. Calculate safety stockf. Calculate target_v00 as Expected_Store_Order + Forecast_Part_Of_Demand + SafetyStockg. Apply target caps & rulesh. Calculate Max SOQ Thresholds
4. Save Dataa. Save Product – Warehouse targets (in case of changing # of active stores during datatransfer, product – warehouse targets are distributed to product – warehouse –stores with a share. During data transfer, these product-warehouse-store values areagain aggregated to product-warehouse level)b. Save report tables, SOQ thresholds, product-store-warehouse log table, productwarehouse log table
5. Insert Data to DB
6. Send control e-mails

· There is a huge data process part that needs to be corporated for each project carefully. Some of the tables may have no use for particular clients.

· Forecast horizon for warehouse replenishment is determined, this is the warehouse cover period but shifted by store cover period duration. Therefore, actual forecast period becomes [TargetDate+StoreCoverPeriod , TargetDate+StoreCoverPeriod+WarehouseCoverPeriod] as range notation.

· Reason of shifting by StoreCoverPeriod can be rephrased as this: Since store targets theoretically cover the demand for StoreCoverPeriod duration, the prediction should be made for the following period.

· Durations are converted into week basis.

the prediction should be made for the following period.

· Durations are converted into week basis.

· Weeks are weighted. In a week, ratio of warehouse cover period span is determined. Assume store cover period as 18 days. In third week, 4 days are covered by store period and 3 days are covered by warehouse period, making the weight 3/7. I could not notice, however we may include day effect as development opportunity.

· Forecasts are aggregated on Store-Product-Warehouse level to reflect total need during the warehouse cover period. Date dimension is therefore disappeared on forecasting part.

· Evaluate the effect of under-excess store order due to the store package size roundings and overstocked inventory supply on warehouse targets:

order due to the store package size roundings and overstocked inventory supply on warehouse targets:

o If store order is greater than zero, there might be additional push caused by package size rounding-ups or low push by rounding-downs. As a result of rounding up, the new target ends up having more coverage than the store cover period duration, hence warehouse forecast can be reduced by that extra. Rounding down has reverse logic, but similarly as well. These differences are reflected into warehouse forecasts as a balance mechanism to prevent over and under forecasting.

o Otherwise, if the order is zero, it theoretically implies that current inventory is high (or equal), therefore higher stock coverage than the store cover period. The extra units on top of the final store target (Inventory OH-StoreTarget) should be eliminated by warehouse forecast to prevent possible overstocking.

ventory OH-StoreTarget) should be eliminated by warehouse forecast to prevent possible overstocking.

· Edited warehouse forecasts are rounded by store package size constraint as well. As an adjustable parameter, half of the round-up values are added to raw warehouse forecasts.

· Aggregate forecasts on Product-Warehouse level.

· Using product based ABC parameters, calculate safety stock with below formula:

SD= a+b*(WDF)^c

SS= z-1(SL) * SD * (WCT)0.5

where WDF is weekly demand forecast for product and WCT is cover time in weeks.

· Warehouse orders are then being generated with respect to the warehouse casepack sizes.
